Data Overview¶

PISA is the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD)'s Programme for International Student Assessment. PISA measures 15-year-olds’ ability to use their reading, mathematics and science knowledge and skills to meet real-life challenges. For this analysis, I focused on resources, mindsets and math outcomes.

NOTE FROM PISA TECHNICAL GUIDE

It cannot be emphasised too strongly that the plausible values are not a substitute for test scores for individuals. Plausible values incorporate responses to test items and information about the background of responses; therefore, they cannot be used to compare individuals.

https://www.oecd.org/pisa/sitedocument/PISA-2015-Technical-Report-Chapter-9-Scaling-PISA-Data.pdf

This is different from the dataset as a whole--LO scoring is significantly more skewed to fewer PCs for Brazilian students. Having several PCs is unlikely for any Vietnamese student, though a greater proportion of LO scoring students have none.

In [116]:
multipropplot_BRVT("BATHROOM", cat_type2, "How Many Baths/Showers at Home");

Also different--HI scoring is skewed more toward more baths/showers for Brazilian students. However, not true for Vietnamese students; HI scoring were most likely to have just one bath/shower.

In [117]:
multipropplot_BRVT("BOOKS", cat_type4, "How Many Books at Home");

Both Vietnamese and Brazilian students have fewer books in general, with 26-100 books being the threshold for the highest proportion of HI scoring students. It seems much less significant for Vietnamese students, where the proportion of LO scoring students even outpaces other groups for more than 500 books.

There isn't significantly more negative mindset in the Brazilian subset; if anything, they showed higher proportions of positive mindsets than the higher scoring Vietnamese students, but there are some interesting differences in resource access. Vietnamese students seemed to have less access to resources than Brazilians. The only measurable where the Vietnamese students clearly outpaced the Brazilians was desk ownership.

Conclusion¶

Viewing the dataset as a whole, and within nations, there were key insights into the correlations between mindset, access, and math PV outcomes. My findings revealed desks, PCs, internet access, and books in the home all positively impact the distritution of PV. As do beliefs about the importance of effort, its relationship to success, perseverance, and perception of parental belief in math importance.

While we could see correlations within the nations, there were not any clear patterns uncovered to explain why Vietnamese students' PV was so much greater than Brazilian students' PV. Perhaps there is a compounding generational factor that isn't sufficiently measured by the current PISA methodology.
